aa(lp380
VWell, what's it like to be this kind of creature?
p381
aVWhat's it like to be one of these brilliant butterflies
p382
aVwho can test five hypotheses in two minutes?
p383
aVWell, if you go back to those psychologists and philosophers,
p384
aVa lot of them have said
p385
aVthat babies and young children were barely conscious
p386
aVif they were conscious at all.
p387
aVAnd I think just the opposite is true.
p388
aVI think babies and children are actually more conscious than we are as adults.
p389
aVNow here's what we know about how adult consciousness works.
p390
aVAnd adults' attention and consciousness
p391
aVlook kind of like a spotlight.
p392
aVSo what happens for adults
p393
aVis we decide that something's relevant or important,
p394
aVwe should pay attention to it.
p395
aVOur consciousness of that thing that we're attending to
p396
aVbecomes extremely bright and vivid,
p397
aVand everything else sort of goes dark.
p398
aVAnd we even know something about the way the brain does this.
p399
aa(lp400
VSo what happens when we pay attention
p401
aVis that the prefrontal cortex, the sort of executive part of our brains,
p402
aVsends a signal
p403
aVthat makes a little part of our brain much more flexible,
p404
aVmore plastic, better at learning,
p405
aVand shuts down activity
p406
aVin all the rest of our brains.
p407
aVSo we have a very focused, purpose-driven kind of attention.
p408
aVIf we look at babies and young children,
p409
aVwe see something very different.
p410
aVI think babies and young children
p411
aVseem to have more of a lantern of consciousness
p412
aVthan a spotlight of consciousness.
p413
aVSo babies and young children are very bad
p414
aVat narrowing down to just one thing.
p415
aVBut they're very good at taking in lots of information
p416
aVfrom lots of different sources at once.
p417
aVAnd if you actually look in their brains,
p418
aVyou see that they're flooded with these neurotransmitters
p419
aVthat are really good at inducing learning and plasticity,
p420
aVand the inhibitory parts haven't come on yet.
p421
aVSo when we say that babies and young children
p422
aVare bad at paying attention,
p423
aVwhat we really mean is that they're bad at not paying attention.
p424
aVSo they're bad at getting rid
p425
aVof all the interesting things that could tell them something
p426
aVand just looking at the thing that's important.
p427
aVThat's the kind of attention, the kind of consciousness,
p428
aVthat we might expect
p429
aVfrom those butterflies who are designed to learn.
